Cross-platform continue-watching sync — live demonstration
===========================================================
Date:    2026-06-17
Target:  deployed exchange-media-core on the NAS, 127.0.0.1:8002,
         MEDIA_INTERNAL_PRINCIPAL_MODE=enforce (fail-closed, real auth boundary)
Crit:    M3 crit 4/5 — same-account continue-watching across platforms (web + tvOS)

What this proves
----------------
Watch/resume state is scoped to the ACCOUNT (`sub`), never the device. The
media-core route resolves the acting user from the *verified internal principal*
(`acting_sub`, crates/media-core/src/routes.rs) — `?sub=` is ignored outside Off
mode (IDOR guard). Two device tokens minted for the SAME account (different
`device_id`) therefore read/write the SAME watch row; a different account is
isolated. This is the backend half of the sync the native iOS/tvOS client
(sibling repo theemeraldexchange-apple, commit 46c2265 "fix(apple): …
continue-watching") consumes over /api/media/watch.

Method
------
- Mint 3 internal principals via `exchange-recommender` (shared
  INTERNAL_PRINCIPAL_SECRET, internal-v1):
    WEB   = sub local:xdevsync,       device_id web-session-A
    TV    = sub local:xdevsync,       device_id appletv-B      (same account, 2nd device)
    OTHER = sub local:xdevsync-other, device_id web-session-C  (different account)
- Drive the real deployed /api/media/watch (POST then GET) as each principal.

Transcript
----------
minted 3 internal principals (web/tvOS same sub local:xdevsync; other=local:xdevsync-other)
movie id under test: 779
--- device A (web) POSTs progress: position_secs=1234 ---
POST http=200
device B (tvOS, same account) sees position_secs = 1234  (expect 1234)
different account sees 0 rows for this movie  (expect 0)
device A (web) re-reads position_secs = 4000  (expect 4000 — tvOS progress synced back)
--- VERDICT ---
PASS: cross-device same-account resume sync + account isolation proven on deployed media-core (enforce mode)

Result
------
PASS. web→tvOS resume (1234 read back on the second device), account isolation
(0 rows for a different account), and bidirectional sync (tvOS advance to 4000
read back by web). Enforce mode, so the identity came from a verified principal,
not a client-supplied sub.

Durable regression floor: the same contract is pinned in CI by
`resume_state_is_account_scoped_across_devices` (crates/media-core/src/routes.rs)
— this live run is the deployed-infra confirmation of that test.

Note: test rows are under throwaway subs (local:xdevsync*), not real accounts —
inert, they never surface on any real user's shelf.
